**I2DL:**

**supervised:** groundtruth labels for training vs. unsupervised: no groundtruth for training  
**unsupervised:** AE, PCA, k-means Clustering

**Classification:** discrete goal \-\> each input is assigned one class  
**Regression:** continuous goal \-\> model predicts continuous value (bound or unbound)

**train:** largest dataset to train model \-\> update weights to extract meaningful features  
**val:** dataset to monitor overfitting by testing models capability to generalize to unseen data; no weight updates but model, and hyperparameters can be changed  
**test:** one-time use of unseen data to have an overall assessment of final model; no changes afterwards

**Shuffle:** shuffle all data to ensure variance among datapoints in train, val, test set; else biased e.g. day-night images  
**Normalization:** data-processing transformations applied to all entire dataset (train, val, test); but for normalization only use train dataset to calculate mean+std \-\> else data leakage

* Linear Regression:  linear; regression; Y \= XW \+ b \-\> for MSE loss function there is closed-form solution due to convex function

* Logistic Regression: non linear\!\!\!; binary classification; uses sigmoid and assigns output a class based on threshold between 0-1

**Activations:**

* apply non-linearity to model  
* vanishing gradient: slows down training due to vanishing (small) gradients for shallower layers \-\> little to no training from them  
  * Reasons:  
    * RNN hidden state weight matrix smaller than 1 \-\> multiplied over multiple time steps \-\> gradient vanishes  
    * sigmoid/tanh  
    * deep networks  
    * xavier weight init  
  * solutions:   
    * full magnitude gradient for positive values with ReLU variation   
    * full magnitude gradient with skip connections  
    * gradient clipping  
* exploding gradient: slows down training due to increasing gradients for shallower layers \-\> deeper layers get neglected for learning  
  * Reasons:  
    * no normalization for activations  
    * bad initialization e.g. large weights  
    * RNN hidden state weight matrix is multiplied many times \-\> gradients explode if it’s \>1  
  * Solutions:  
    * gradient clipping  
    * normalization (BN, LayerN)  
    * weight initialization  
* Dead ReLU= gradient flow is immediately \+ permanently killed for shallower layers if negative input \-\> 0 \-\> gradient zero \-\> limits network capacity to learn  
  * Reasons:  
    * bad init  
  * solutions:  
    * ReLU variant like leaky ReLU  
    * Kaiming initialization prevents this


* Sigmoid  
  * element-wise  
  * easy calculation, 0-1 good binary/probability representation  
  * Drawbacks  
    * saturation for small/large inputs \-\> vanishing gradient  
    * biggest gradient: 0.25 at 0 \-\> small  
    * not zero-centered

![][image4]             ![][image5]

* Tanh  
  * element-wise  
  * zero-centered  
  * Drawbacks:  
    * small effective range \[-2, 2\] \-\> vanishing gradient else  
    * biggest gradient at 0: 1

![][image6]        ![][image7]        ![][image8]

* ReLU  
  * element-wise  
  * simple, computationally efficient   
  * solves vanishing gradient \-\> full magnitude gradient for positive values  
  * Drawbacks:  
    * not zero-centered  
    * non differentiable at 0  
    * dying ReLU   
    * (exploding gradient)  
* Leaky/Parametric ReLU or ELU  
  * element-wise  
  * leaky is fixed alpha / parametric is learned alpha  
  * zero-centered  
  * Drawbacks:  
    * introduce hyper param or are more expensive to compute  
    * still not differentiable at 0 \-\> numerical instability  
* Softmax  
  * full-vector  
  * distribution of input values from 0 to 1 summing to 1  
  * often to avoid numerical instability \-\> shifted by max(x) \-\> same value but less cost

![][image9]

**Loss Functions:**   
\! guide weights through BP (and then also assess models performance)  
Don’t forget 1/R at beginning: R=\#residuals (N: samples)

- for classification: R \= N (image to image)  
- for segmentation: R \= NxHxW (all pixels)  
- for image reconstruction: R \= NxHxWxC (all pixels per channel)

always results in scalar else computationally expensive jacobian derivative

* BCE  
  * used with Sigmoid  
  * binary classification \-\> one neuron  
  * numerical instability for log(0) \-\> use gradient clipping  
* CE  
  * softmax (not sigmoid as sum of probs has to be 1\)  
  * multiclass classification  
  * for binary it uses two neuros  
  * numerical instability for log(0) \-\> use gradient clipping  
  * \- 1/R log(y\_pred)     for one sample 1/R fällt weg  
  * in first iteration initialized with random weights \-\> \-log(1/\#classes)  
* MAE \= L1 loss  
  * sparser loss distribution  
  * robust to outliers  
  * not differentiable at 0

![][image10]

* MSE \= L2 Loss  
  * shares loss among samles \-\> blurry reconstruction  
  * sensitive to outliers

![][image11]

**Regularization:**  
\= make training harder to ensure generalization (or add additional goal/constraint to training)

* L1 / L2 regularization terms  
  * both push sum of weights to zero  
  * applied in loss function\!  
  * L1 ![][image12] sparse penalty \-\> pushed some weights to zero

		\-\> feature selection of most important ones (detects redundant ones)

* L2 ![][image13]more equal / distributed penalty \-\> more similar weights 

		\-\> easier computation

* Weight decay  
  * applied in optimizer step\!  
    ![][image14]  
  * supervised by learning rate  
  * uses L2  
  * lambda is decay coefficient


* Data augmentation  
  * artificially increases size of dataset   
  * to supplement settings variance or small data set \-\> reduce overfitting  
  * only applied to train data, as val and test data distributions should remain original for assessment of generalization  
  * regularization technique as it makes training harder with new and different datapoints \-\> but helps generalization  
  * \! before augmenting watch out that it’s appropriate or that groundtruth gets changed accordingly  
      
* Dropout  
  * like ensemble: by using same train set in multiple models (models with different activated neurons)  
  * hyperparam p decides probability of dropping or keeping a neuron  
  * dropout after activation  
  * inverse dropout more efficient for inference \-\> already scale remaining neurons with 1/p\_keep  
      
* Batchnorm  
  * introduces noise cause only batch approximation of entire statistics of training set \-\> regularization (but not go to for overfitting problem)  
  * helps to go deeper with layers   
  * only layer to break abstraction of independent samples in batch  
  * dims of gamma and beta are same \-\> 2\*...  
    1. for affine: number of neurons  
    2. for convs: number of channels  
  * for backprop: ![][image15]  
  * x gets normalized with mean and variance of batch \-\> the bigger batch the better approximation  
  * gamma and beta are learnable params to undo scaling and shifting in training  
  * in inference it uses running mean and std of training as for batch\_size \= 1 \-\> no approximation of statistics possible  
  * types of BN:  
    1. BN \= across all features of all instances in batch  
    2. layer N \= across all features of an instance  
    3. instance N \= for conv independent channels  
    4. group norm \= works for batch\_size \< 16; divides channels to groups \-\> layer N is group norm for \#groups=1

**Optimizer:**  
in gradient descent gradient is subtracted cause it shows direction of steepest ascend but we want to minimize

* GD  
  * optimization step after each epoch  
  * first order  
  * without approximation noise \-\> gets stuck at saddle point  
  * computationally expensive  
  * takes long  
* SGD  
  * optimization step after each batch iteration  
  * first order  
  * noise of gradient approximation for batch \-\> allows to overcome saddle points  
  * converges faster  
    ![][image16] 	alpha is learning rate  
* SGD Momentum  
  * first order  
  * ![][image17]  
  * ß momentum coefficient usually 0.9  
  * when gradient big (slope steep) \-\> bigger update step  \-\> faster convergence  
  * allows to overcome saddle points  
  * has noisy optimization trajectory  
* (Nestrov Momentum \-\> look ahead / not better than ADAM)  
* RMSprop   
  * fixes noisy optimization trajectory of SGD (+ Momentum)  
  * introduces second order moment to dampen oscillations in direction of gradient \-\> allows higher learning rate (scales learning rate of each weight independently) / faster convergence   
  * scales learning rate individually for each weights  
* ADAM  
  * first and second order  
  * combines RMSprop \+ (SGD) Momentum  
  * bias correction: as m, v get initialised with 0 \-\> bias towards zero \-\> divide with 1-ß^t-1 to correct it \-\> bias correction will vanish the higher t becomes/for later iterations   
  * (ß is \<1\!) ß is decay rate coefficient of moving average of first/second moment mean/variance gradients  
* Gauß-Newton method  
  * needs less iterations and no learning rate  
  * uses inverse Hessian matrix to approximate optima using all data points \-\> need to be loaded into RAM (computationally expensive\!\!)  
      
* Weight Initialization:  
  * need to be randomly initialized from distribution else if similar \-\> same updates \-\> underfit  
  * Xavier:   
    * Var(X\_t+1) \= Var(X)     Note: X\_t+1 \= Y   
    * Var(W) \= 1/n und mean\_weights \= 0  
    * keeps activations in meaningful magnitude \-\> avoids vanishing gradient \+ allows deeper layers  
    * mostly for sigmoid and tanh  
  * Kaiming:  
    * specialized for ReLU \-\> addressing dead ReLU problem  
    * Var(W) \= 2/n

    

* Overfitting  
  * when generalization gap increases due to training loss still decreasing/being low and validation loss starting to increase again \-\> train loss low \+ val loss high \-\> fails to generalize  
  * Reasons:  
    * small dataset \-\> no general patterns extracted  
    * too many parameters \-\> memorizes data  
    * training too long \-\> not stopped early enough, noise i learned after important features  
  * Solutions:  
    * regularization  
      * dropout  
      * data augmentation  
      * weight decay  
      * (BN)  
    * early stopping  
* Underfitting  
  * detected when validation and training loss converge at high loss (noted from models accuracy e.g.) or when both are still decreasing as training stops  
  * Reasons:  
    * not enough model capacity \-\> bad/small model to learn patterns  
    * not enough training \-\> not converged to minima yet  
    * stuck at saddle point  
    * overshoots minima due to high learning rate  
  * Solutions:  
    * increase models capacity: layers or different architecture  
    * train for more epochs  
    * better optimization algorithm \-\> not get stuck at saddle points  
    * learning rate decay \-\> model doesn’t overshoot  
* Mismatch in distribution/Imbalanced data \-\> shuffle data\! (train and val loss completely different)  
* Validation set too easy/data leakage \-\> validation loss below training loss

**Transfer Learning:**

1) pretrained model for large dataset like AlexNet and then finetune on small dataset  
2) pretrain AE on reconstruction for large unlabelled data \-\> use encoder as pretrained feature extractor \+ classifier on small labeled dataset  
* used for limited data or lack of resources 


  
**Convolutions**:

* fewer params; local features; fewer calculations; faster, smaller model  
* can take arbitrary input sizes but suboptimal if trained on different size  
* works through all channels of neighborhood  
* \#params \= \#c\_in x \#c\_out/num\_kernels x (kernel\_h x kernel\_w)  \+ \#c\_out (bias)  
* equivariant/robust to translation not rotation  
* formula for new output size after kernel:![][image18]  
* formula receptive field:![][image19]  
* receptive field always full input image (at beginning) for FC layer  
* for k=3, s=1, p=1  or k=1, s=1, p=0 (point-wise convs) \-\> spatial size doesnt change  
* k=3, s=2, p=1 \-\> spatial size is halved  
* if stride step does not fit window \-\> information lost  
* transform FC layer to convs:  
  * take kernel of input size with \#kernels \= \#classes 

    \-\> flatten \#classes x 1 x 1

**upsample:** linear, no learnable params  
**transpose convs:** non-linear, learnable params  
**1x1 convolutions:** cheap; preserve spatial dims but can increase/decrease channels; receptive field is same

handcrafted kernels: useful for data augment or weight init  
depthwise-convs: channel-wise convs \-\> channels stay same

**Pooling:**

* no learnable params  
* channel-wise  
* MaxPool:  
  * non-linear  
  * with k=2, s=2 \-\> only quarter of inputs get gradient if all values unique \-\> more if multiple max\_values  
  * rest 0 \-\> necessary to cache index of values for backprop  
* Average Pooling  
  * linear operation

Architectures:

* AE  
  * made up of FC layers and non-linear activations \-\> non-linear model  
  * encoder: reduces dimensionality and compresses input image to latent space while also extracting meaningful features  
  * latent space: powerful representation of compressed input image   
    * if too small \-\> reconstruction not possible; too much info lost; underfit  
    * if too big \-\> model can just memorize inputs \-\> overfit  
  * decoder: reconstructs image from latent space  
  * reconstruction loss e.g. MSE, MAE  
* UNet  
  * fully convolutional AE with skip connections  
  * skip connections make sense for depth estimation/segmantic segmentation but not cases where input \= output (reconstruction) cause skip connections allow model to cheat/memorize \-\> overfit  
  * also if encoder and decoder are separated \-\> skip connections won’t work  
  * encoder: increases channels to mitigate loss of spatial dims  
  * decoder: decreases channels to avoid expensive calculations  
  * latent space: not only vector like in AE but BxCxHxW   
  * reconstruction loss e.g. MSE, MAE  
  * advantages over AE:  
    * less computational cost due to convolutions  
    * skip connections   
    * inputs of all sizes   
    * locality features  
* VAE  
  * generative model  
  * generates image from sample noise with decoder (encoder gets discarded for inference)  
  * encoder encodes distribution (two vectors: compressed mean and variance of data) into latent space  
  * parametrization trick \= scale and shift sample noise from normal distribution to learned distribution  
  * reconstruction loss e.g. MSE, MAE \+ KL-divergence loss (distribution loss)  
  * **Differences to AE:**  
    * not single vector but two (compressed mean and variance) in latent space  
    * additional loss function (KL-divergence)  
* GAN  
  * generative model  
  * learns implicitly \<-\> VAE learns explicitly  
  * Decoder as generator to generate fake image from gaussian noise  
  * this and a real image are inputs to discriminator (encoder \+ classifier) which distinguishes between real (label 1\) and fake image (label 0\)  
  * then the weights of discriminator get updated  
  * then input only the fake image with label 1 and only update the generators weights  
    \-\> both parts of model are updated independently (2 backprobs) \-\> min max balance  
    \-\> hard to train as generator and discriminator compete (generator tries to fool discriminator) \-\> possible to find suboptimal minima  
* RNN  
  * shared weights among all inputs/timesteps \-\> three Weight matrices for X, h and o output  
  * calc curr hidden state h\_t \= A( x\_t \* W\_x \+ h\_t-1 \* W\_h \+ b\_h)  
  * use in output o\_t \= A ( h\_t \* W\_h \+ b\_o)  
  * if hidden state of previous layers gets inputted into new layers the W\_h multiply  
  * hidden state weight gets multiplied for every input to the RNN \-\> for 3 inputs it's Wh^3 \-\> if Wh \< 1 it will get vanishingly small (likewise gradients) ; if Wh \> 1 gradients will explode  
  * advantages:  
    * model any input/output (one-one, many-one, many-many etc)  
    * sequential data (short-term memory/hiddenstate)  
  * shortcomings:   
    * small capacity due to only 3 weight matrices  
    * no long-term memory  
    * vanishing/exploding gradients  
* LSTM  
  * addresses vanishing gradient problem of RNN  
  * \-\> allows longer input sequences/more capacity  
  * solution: use two paths 1\) short term memory 2\) long term memory without weights  
  * forget layer: uses sigmoid to determine how much of previous cell state is kept  
  * input/update layer: tanh generates candidate values/new information to be remembered in cell state and sigmoid decides how much of it should be kept and forwarded to cell  
  * output layer: uses tanh to get potential short term memory from cell state \-\> sigmoid decides how much gets into output hidden state   
  * shortcomings:   
  * bias towards more recent inputs  
  * hidden state compresses entire past \-\> a lot of lost information  
  * hard to train (iterative through all states/timesteps)  
* Transformer  
  * less bias towards more recent inputs (like in RNN, LSTM)  
  * attention mechanism is equivariant to sequential order  
* Diffusion models  
  * generative model  
  * gradually add noise to input image at each time step t \-\> x\_0 input \-\> x\_T full noise  
  * model is trained for reversed process (probabilistic model \-\> always different output)  
  * 2 approaches  
  * 1\) autoencoder add noise then encode decode to denoise  
  * 2\) add noise in latent space  
  * very scalable, sota  
  * many steps necessary

Popular Architectures

* LeNet ((2 x Conv \+ Pool ) \+ Conv \+ 2x FC)  
  * convolutions to compress input images and extract local features  
  * FC layers for classification based on global features  
  * avg pool and tanh \+ sigmoid \-\> maxpool more common as it has NL \+ vanishing gradient problem for sigmoid/tanh  
  * change of input image not possible due to fixed FC layers  
* AlexNet  
  * went deep  
  * many params due to FC layer  
  * 11x11 kernel \-\> 1\) computationally expensive 2\) loss of locality  
  * add more layers \-\> vanishing gradients  
  * MaxPool \-\> RGARAGGAERW  
  * ReLU \-\> AGAGAEge  
  * change of input image not possible due to fixed FC layers  
* VGGNet  
  * large, simple model  
  * 3x3 convs improvement from 11x11 from AlexNet (less comp cost \+ better locality)  
  * output softmax part of network \-\> should be part of loss function not network  
* ResNet  
  * skip connections/highway of gradient \= allow gradients to flow through the network \-\> meaningful gradient for shallower layeers  
  * goes both directions  
  * ![][image20]  
  * allows to go deeper  
  * python implementation: ![][image21]  
* Inception layers  
  * use multiple kernel sizes \-\> very expensive, especially for larger kernel size  
  * use maxpool 3x1x1 to maintain all spatial sizes/concatenate all results  
  * to address high computational cost 1x1 convs were introduced to reduce channels
